This is a revival of  https://github.com/openfisca/openfisca-core/pull/378, but differently implemented, with the needed cache adaptation.

The idea is to allow a formula to take an extra parameter. For instance : 
```py
class ppa_fictive(Variable):
    # (...)
    def function(self, simulation, period, reference_period):

class ppa(Variable):
    # (...)
    def function(self, simulation, period):
        period2 = period.last_month # for example
        simulation.calculate('ppa_fictive', period2, extra_params = [period])
```

The cache has been adapted so that is doesn't return a value cached for a specific set of extra parameters when called with a different one. In this case, the content of the cache would be:
```py
holder._array_by_period[period] = 
    { (param_value_1,) : result1, (param_value_2,) : result2 }
```
I slightly refactored it, trying to expose two clearly named methods to the outside : `put_in_cache(self, value, period, extra_params = None)` and `get_from_cache(self, period, extra_params = None)`.

I also adapted the conversion to JSON (here and in the API). 
```json
"ppa_fictive": {
    "2015-11": {
        "{reference_period: 2015-12}": 533.10595703125,
        "{reference_period: 2016-01}": 377.430419921875
    },
    "2015-10": {
        "{reference_period: 2015-12}": 428.10595703125,
        "{reference_period: 2016-01}": 272.430419921875
    },
    "2015-12": 283.0704345703125,
    "2015-09": 0
},
```
As long as there is only one result, for a variable and a period, there will be no difference with the actual behavior. The json will be more complex only if a formula has been called with two different set of extra parameters. This happens for instance with ppa if you compute it for several months in a row.

This is a new class which describes the local personal endpoint. It has one property: endpoint_id, which gets the endpoint ID as a string.

@jaswilli mentioned maybe not including a deleter for `LocalGlobusConnectPersonal.endpoint_id` -- I don't have much of an opinion on this.
I could also remove it from the docstring for the `endpoint_id` property, to keep the docs simpler and shorter, but I'd leave the actual deleter in place, if we think it might be confusing to novice users.

Hey folks - here's an implementation for a new ```format``` function in conform as proposed in https://github.com/openaddresses/openaddresses/pull/1925. It allows for more flexibility than ```join``` when mapping multiple input fields to a single field in the output CSV.

Given the following config:
```json
{
    "conform": {
        "number": {
            "function": "format",
            "fields": ["a", "b", "c"],
            "format": "$1$2-$3"
        }
    }
}
```

and these inputs:

```json
{"a": "1", "b": "B", "c": "3"}
```

It will produce ```{"OA:number": "1B-3"}```.

If one of the variables is NULL/empty, its left context will be omitted, except for any initial string that appears before the first variable occurrence. So for the format string above, if "c" is NULL, it will produce ```{"OA:number": "1B"}```, omitting the hyphen.

This is one alternative. It's also possible to implement using Python format strings, allowing type conversion, etc. but that syntax (especially in Python 3 after they decided to depart from the C-style format strings) may be unfamiliar to non-Python users. This simple format aims to mimic bash args or regex groups, hence the counting from 1 business, which should be familiar to most developers regardless of language background.

